// Using Set to remove duplicates
const arrayWithDuplicates = [1, 2, 2, 3, 4, 4, 5];
const uniqueArrayUsingSet = [...new Set(arrayWithDuplicates)];
console.log(uniqueArrayUsingSet); // Output: [1, 2, 3, 4, 5]

// Using filter and indexOf to remove duplicates
const uniqueArrayUsingFilter = arrayWithDuplicates.filter((item, index) => {
  return arrayWithDuplicates.indexOf(item) === index;
});
console.log(uniqueArrayUsingFilter); // Output: [1, 2, 3, 4, 5]

// Using reduce to remove duplicates
const uniqueArrayUsingReduce = arrayWithDuplicates.reduce((accumulator, current) => {
  if (!accumulator.includes(current)) {
    accumulator.push(current);
  }
  return accumulator;
}, []);
console.log(uniqueArrayUsingReduce); // Output: [1, 2, 3, 4, 5]
```

These are a few simple JavaScript tricks to effectively remove duplicate elements from an array. Each method offers a different approach, allowing you to choose the one that best fits your coding style and performance needs.
